    <theorem xml:id="theorem-limit-laws-1">
        <title>Limit Laws, I</title>
            <statement>
            <p>
                Let <m>b</m>, <m>c</m>, <m>L</m>, and <m>K</m> be real numbers, let <m>n</m> be a positive integer, and let <m>f</m> and <m>g</m> be functions defined on an open interval <m>I</m> containing <m>c</m> satisfying<me>
                \lim_{x \to c} f(x) = L \text{and} \lim_{x \to c} g(x) = K
                </me>. Then we have the following limits as well.
                <ol>
                    <li><m>\lim_{x \to c} b = b</m></li>
                    <li><m>\lim_{x \to c} x = c</m></li>
                    <li><m>\lim_{x \to c} (f(x) \pm g(x)) = L \pm K</m></li>
                    <li><m>\lim_{x \to c} b \cdot f(x) = bL</m></li>
                    <li><m>\lim_{x \to c} f(x) \cdot g(x) = LK</m></li>
                    <li><m>\lim_{x \to c} f(x) / g(x) = L/K</m> (provided that <m>K \ne 0</m></li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </theorem>
    <theorem xml:id="theorem-limit-laws-2">
        <title>Limit Laws, II</title>
        <statement>
            <p>foo</p>
            <ol>
                <li><m>\lim_{x \to c} f(x)^n = L^n</m></li>
                <li><m>\lim_{x \to c} \sqrt[n]{f(x)} = \sqrt[n]{L}</m></li>
                <li><m>composition</m></li>
            </ol>
        </statement>
    </theorem>
    <activity xml:id="activity-limits-analytically3">
        <statement>
            <p>If <m>\lim f(x) = 2</m> and <m>\lim g(x) = -3</m>, which of the following statements are true?</p>
            <ol>
                <li><m>\lim (f(x) \cdot g(x)) = -6</m></li>
                <li><m>\lim (f(x) + g(x)) = -1</m></li>
                <li><m>\lim (f(x) - g(x)) = -2</m></li>
                <li><m>\lim (f(x)/g(x)) = -2/3</m></li>
            </ol>
        </statement>
    </activity>
